My understanding is that the Father is God acting as the Creator of the Earth and the cosmos. He is the entity that established the original covenant with Abraham and his descendants through Jacob (the Hebrews), and spoke to Moses to establish his commandments. The God of the Old Testament.
Christ, the Son, is the Redeemer. God incarnated Himself as the son of a Hebrew maiden (Mary). This son, Jesus, roamed around Galilee, performing miracles such as healing the sick and feeding the hungry before dying on the cross. He did this deliberately, sacrificing himself to cleanse mankind of sin. Through Him, the old covenant was abandoned, and a new one was established, open not only to the Hebrews but to all who accept Him and His sacrifice.
Christ resurrected from the dead shortly after his sacrifice, assembled his disciples, and forgave them of their sins before ascending into heaven. After this, the Holy Spirit appeared before Christ's followers, filling their hearts with joy and warmth, and granting them the courage to spread the word of the new covenant. The Holy Spirit guides men to act in accordance with God's will, although it's ultimately our own choice to follow through.
